    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, n. <citedRange>2</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.327</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>031100</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#forbes1956"/><citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>16.872</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#lazzarini1998"/>, p. <citedRange>311</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Zeus_Melichios"><name nymRef="#Ζεύς"><supplied reason="lost">Ζ</supplied><unclear>ε̄</unclear>νὶ</name> 
                        <rs type="epithet" key="Melichios"><name nymRef="#Μηλίχιος">Με̄<supplied reason="lost">λιχίōι</supplied></name></rs></persName>,
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eumenis"><name nymRef="#Εὐμενίς"><expan><abbr><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Εὐμε</supplied></abbr><ex>νίσι</ex></expan></name></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eumenis"><name nymRef="#Εὐμενίς"><expan><abbr><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Εὐμ</supplied></abbr><ex>ενίσι</ex></expan></name></persName> 
                            <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Δάμας"><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Δάμας</supplied></name></persName>.

	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <lem><supplied reason="lost">Ζ</supplied><unclear>ε̄</unclear>νὶ</lem>
                        <rdg resp="#SEG"><supplied reason="lost">Ζ</supplied>ηνί</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="3">
                        <lem><expan><abbr><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Εὐμ</supplied></abbr><ex>ενίσι</ex></expan> Δάμας</lem> 
                        <rdg resp="#ferri1923"><expan><abbr>Ευμ</abbr><ex>ενίδων</ex></expan><expan><abbr>Δαμασ</abbr><ex>ιστράτω</ex></expan> <note>personal name completed exempli gratia</note></rdg>
                        <rdg resp="#SEG 9"><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63880"><name>Εὐ<choice><corr>ρυ</corr><sic>μ</sic></choice>δάμας</name></persName></rdg>
                    </app>
                </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>À Zeus Mélikhios et aux Euménides. Aux Euménides Damas <supplied reason="subaudible" cert="low">a consacré</supplied>.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>To Zeus Melichios and to the Eumenides. To the Eumenides Damas <supplied reason="subaudible" cert="low">dedicated</supplied>.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>A Zeus Melichios e alle Eumenidi. Alle Eumenidi Damas <supplied reason="subaudible" cert="low">ha dedicato</supplied>.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p><foreign xml:lang="grc">Δάμας</foreign> being a good personal name, it is probably associated at line 3 with an abbreviated form of the name of 
                the Eumenides, as it is just above and also in other inscriptions of this group at Ain Hofra.</p>
          	<p>Differently from nearby inscriptions, this one was cut directly on the rocky cliff and not associated with an altar. Another difference is the dative case 
    	of the divine names, indicating a formula of dedication.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
